name: Azaelea
description: In Japan and China, azaeleas symbolize remembrance of home and the desire to return and family. Victorians saw these flowers as a symbol of temperance and elegance. Though due to their toxicity, azaeleas delivered in a black vase once symbolized a death threat.

name: Cherry Blossom
description: In Japan, the cherry blossom holds strong symbolism for spring and renewal, as well as the fleeting nature of life due to the short period of time cherry blossoms bloom. It also symbolizes kindness, gentleness, feminine beauty, and mono no aware.

name: Chyrsanthemum
description: Generally symbolizes longevity, fidelity, joy, and optimism, many cultures had different symbolism associated with Chrysanthemums. The Victorians believed this flower conveyed friendship and well-wishing. The Buddhists used chrysanthemums as an offering due to their powerful Yang energy. The Chinese offered these flowers to the elderly to promote a long life and good luck in the home and Belgium and Austria almost exclusively use them as a memorial flower to honor loved ones who've passed.

name: Hydrangea
description: Hydrangeas have connections to strong emotions in their symbolism, such as giving them to love interests when rejected to show that they are cold hearted. The Victorians specifically associated the flower with vanity and boastfulness. However, the Japanese use this flower to convey a heartfelt apology and gratitude for understanding.

name: Lotus
description: Symbolizing rebirth and triumph over obstacles, lotus flowers are common in religions for divinity and virtues. In Buddhisim, the lotus flower symbolizes the journey of life, it's struggles, and practicing non-attachment. In Hinduism, it symbolizes divinity, purity, enlightment, and the disconnect with worldly things.

name: Poppy
description: Poppies convey contrasting meanings in different cultures. In Egyptian and Greek cultures, poppies symbolize restful sleep and recovery due to the medicinal properties that assist in sleeping. similarly, the Victorians poppies conveyed consolation for a loss in the family, deep sleep, and extravagance. For East Asia, red poppies symbolize success, beauty, and love while white poppies mean death. In contrast, Western cultures use red poppies symbolize death, specifically remembrance for veterans who've passed and white poppies convey peaceful rest.
